Work with the RC Centre for Professional Skills team and Commerce course instructors and their TAs on deliverables related to the development of professional skills. Duties may include facilitating group and individual appointments with students and providing support for students in developing both written and oral communication skills. This could include:
-	providing feedback on drafts of written assignments and support for building effective writing skills;
-	providing support for both individual and group written assignments;
-	providing feedback on drafts of video-based oral communication assessments and support for effective video presentations;
-	providing oral communication coaching and feedback; 
-	providing support for both individual and group video presentations.

Duties and appointments will be delivered primarily remotely/online, using WCOnline and other platforms such as Zoom or Teams. Some sessions will be delivered in person, to be scheduled in consultation with the TA, depending on schedule and preference. 

Duties may also include the development of teaching resources related to oral or written communication skills, or presentation skills.

Work with the RC Centre for Professional Skills team and Commerce course instructors and their TAs on deliverables related to the development of professional skills (e.g. professional written and oral communication, teamwork skills, intercultural competencies). Duties may include:
-	providing support for the grading of online modules embedded in RC courses;
-	facilitating workshops focusing on the development of professional skills;
-	providing overall support for CPS instructional programming.
Duties may also include facilitating or co-facilitating TA training or marking calibration sessions and/or providing research support on pedagogical projects. Additional support on resource design and creation related to supporting students’ professional skills may also be included.

The TA will work closely with the instructors and the class to achieve the following, in-person and online:
i) the development of critical, timely and relevant background materials and case studies to support in-class exercises and students’ individual and group graded assignments on applied policy development and implementation;
ii) critical and timely feedback to the lectures based on own MPP1 or other experience and class, on the course syllabus, readings, examples and exercises;
iii) development, co-ordination and delivery of course related workshops;
iv) preliminary marking of some assignments;
v) clear communications across the sections regarding instructor expectations and assignments;
vi) effective liaison with guest speakers around their topics, dates, logistics;
vii) other duties as assigned

